**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Animal Rights</span>**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> – Human rights</span>
**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> 1. Syllogism</span>**
a. Animal rights refer to a liberty granted to one or more animal species. **Merriam-Webster[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Sept-Oct/Aff/Flow%20Aff%20-%20Human%20Rights.docx#_ftn2|**[2]**]]** defines it:
**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">rights </span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">(as to fair and humane treatment) </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">regarded as belonging fundamentally to any animal</span>__**

<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">This denotation must be preferred to any animal rights such as welfare or other opposing definitions, because it incorporates those definitions into a broad definition that augments the scope, and thusly the education of the debate.</span>
b. Homo Sapiens are animals. By neglecting to acknowledge that human beings also fall under this premise of animal rights, we will be enhancing the present speciesism in the real world. **Dunayer[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Sept-Oct/Aff/Flow%20Aff%20-%20Human%20Rights.docx#_ftn3|**[3]**]]** writes:
**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">When used to denote other species only, //animal// falsely removes humans from animalkind.</span>__** <span style="font-size: 5pt;">In parallel, through their male imagery the pseudogenerics //man// and //mankind// effectively exclude women from humankind. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">By reserving //animal// for //other// animals, humans deny their kinship with nonhuman animals, abjuring membership in all groups larger than species</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> – such as primatekind, mammalkind, and animalkind. </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">This use of //animal// reflects the speciesist belief that humans fundamentally differ from all nonhuman animals and are inherently superior</span>__**<span style="font-size: 8pt;">.”</span>
c. Therefore, animal rights can refer to a liberty granted to homo sapiens. Hence, the definition is allowed under the syntax of the resolution.

**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> 2. </span>****<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Humans are the only animals that can have rights</span>**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Rights create an obligation, or contract, between the rights-bearers, and thus nonhuman animals cannot have rights. **Scruton[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Sept-Oct/Aff/Flow%20Aff%20-%20Human%20Rights.docx#_ftn4|**[4]**]]** reads:</span>
<span style="font-size: 5pt;">Still, there are limits. Rights may have taken precedence over duties, but American jurisprudence has always been clear that </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">rights cannot be had for free. Every legal privilege creates a burden on the one who does not possess it: your right may be my duty, and people who claim rights are also in the business of respecting them</span>__**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">. **__Rights cannot be invented without also inventing the social and legal relations that enable us to uphold them, and__** </span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">the shopping list of </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">rights will therefore be </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">severely</span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">limited</span>__**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **__by__** </span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">social custom and </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">human nature</span>__**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">. </span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">The conservative hope is that, at a certain point, common sense will prevail. "If you invent any more rights," people then will say, "you will find yourself in a society where nobody respects them. In other words, you will have destroyed the very benefit that you sought to extend." And it seems to me that the birth of "communitarianism" as a posture within the American liberal tradition is really a recognition of this possibility, and of the underlying truth that a society cannot be based in rights alone but must also inculcate a strong sense of duty in its members, if rights are to be anything more than useless bits of paper. Rights ought not to be given but purchased, and the price is duty. You can have many things on the cheap; but the moral life isn't one of them.</span>
<span style="font-size: 5pt;">But this brings us face-to-face with what is, to my mind, the strangest cultural shift within the liberal worldview, one that promises to sow even more confusion than liberalism inherently requires: the growing advocacy of "animal rights." </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Properly understood, the concept of a right—</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">and </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">the attendant ideas of duty, responsibility, law, and obedience—enshrines what is distinctive in the human condition</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">. To spread the concept beyond our species is to jeopardize our dignity as moral beings, who live in judgment of one another and of themselves.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">To build upon this responsibility that rights entail: Rights require that you take others rights into consideration when you act, and thusly impose positive and negative duties – which nonhuman animals can’t uphold. **Cohen[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Sept-Oct/Aff/Flow%20Aff%20-%20Human%20Rights.docx#_ftn5|**[5]**]]** explains:</span>
<span style="font-size: 5pt;">The differing targets, contents, and sources of rights, and their inevitable conflict, together weave a tangled web. Notwithstanding all such complications, this much is clear about </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">rights</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">in general: they </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">are</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">in every case</span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">claims</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, or potential claims, </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">within a community of moral agents. Rights arise, and can be intelligibly defended, only among beings who actually</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">do, or </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">can, make moral</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">claims against one another</span>__**<span style="font-size: 6pt;">. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Whatever else rights may be, therefore, they are necessarily human</span>__**<span style="font-size: 6pt;">; </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">their possessors are</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">persons, </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">human beings</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Secondly, rights bearers must be able to step outside of their own self-interests in order to do what is just for the whole moral community. **Cohen 2** reads:</span>
