<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">This prospect stems from a new understanding of how mammals sense pain. </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">The brain</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">, it turns out, </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">has two separate pathways for perceiving pain: a sensory pathway that registers its location</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">, quality (sharp, dull or burning, for example) and intensity</span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">, and a so-called affective pathway that senses the pain’s unpleasantness. This second pathway appears to be associated with activation of the brain’s anterior cingulate cortex, because people who have suffered damage to this part of the brain </span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">still feel pain but </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">no longer find it unpleasant.</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;"> (The same is true of people who are given morphine, because there are more receptors for opiates in the affective pain pathway than in the sensory pain pathway.)</span>

