===Will to Power/Subjectivity AC=== 
<span style="display: block; text-align: center;">
</span>
**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Definitions:</span>**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">I define **moral obligation** as the individuals Will to Power. Nietzsche first describes what the Will to Power is in **Nietzsche 1[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn1|**[1]**]]:**</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Only where there is life, is there also will: not, however, Will</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">to Life, but- so teach I thee- Will to Power!</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">Much is reckoned higher than life itself by the living one; butout of the very reckoning speaketh- the Will to Power!"-Thus did Life once teach me: and thereby, ye wisest ones, do I solveyou the riddle of your hearts</span><span style="font-size: 7pt;">.</span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Verily, I say unto you: good and evil which would be everlasting- it</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">doth not exist! Of its own accord must it ever surpass itself anew. With your values and formulae of good and evil, ye exercise power,</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">ye valuing ones</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">: and that is your secret love, and the sparkling,trembling, and overflowing of your souls.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Here, Nietzsche explains that instead of binding to society’s morals and projections of good and evil, we must use our own values and justifications to determine morality. I define the Will to Power as: the driving force that allows individuals to develop morals, gain self-conscientiousness, and reach their potential. This is the motive which establishes obligations. **Nietzsche 2[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn2|**[2]**]]** writes:</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">A man who WILLS commands something within himself which renders obedience, or which he believes renders obedience.</span>__****<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> But now let us notice what is the strangest thing about the will,-this affair so extremely complex, for which the people have only one name. </span>****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Inasmuch as in the given circumstances we are at the same time the commanding AND the obeying parties</span>__****<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, and as the obeying party we know the sensations of constraint, impulsion, pressure, resistance, and motion, which usually commence immediately after the act of will; inasmuch as, on the other hand, </span>****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">we are accustomed to disregard this duality, and to deceive ourselves about it by means of the synthetic term "I": a whole series</span>__****<span style="font-size: 5pt;">of erroneous conclusions, and consequently of </span>****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">false judgments about the will itself, has become attached to the act of willing-to such a degree that he who wills believes firmly that willing SUFFICES for action</span>__****<span style="font-size: 5pt;">. Since in the majority of cases there has only been exercise of will when the effect of the command-consequently obedience, and therefore action-was to be EXPECTED, the APPEARANCE has translated itself into the sentiment, as if there were a NECESSITY OF EFFECT; in a word</span>****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">, he who wills believes with a fair amount of certainty that will and action are somehow one; he ascribes the success, the carrying out of the willing, to the will itself, and thereby enjoys an increase of the sensation of power which accompanies all success</span>__****<span style="font-size: 5pt;">. "Freedom of Will"-that is the expression for the complex state of delight of the person exercising volition, who commands and at the same time identifies himself with the executor of the order- who, as such, enjoys also the triumph over obstacles, but thinks within himself that it was really his own will that overcame them. In this way the person exercising volition adds the feelings of delight of his successful executive instruments, the useful "underwills" or under-souls-indeed, our body is but a social structure composed of many souls-to his feelings of delight as commander.</span>**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Therefore, the Will to Power inherently establishes a moral obligation on the actor of such will. Thus the Will to Power is a means of obligations, and a sufficient obligation for affirming the resolution.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">I define **Individuals** and **People** as more than one person, but not necessarily every person, because it would be unfeasible and completely ridiculous for the affirmative to prove that every individual has a moral obligation to everyone else’s well-being. Eisenhower in no way should have had an obligation to Hitler, and insofar as there are exceptions to the rule, the rule cannot stand. Thus I don’t have to prove a totality, but rather that a general amount of individuals have a moral obligation to a general amount of other people.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">I reserve the right to clarify any other definitions in cross-x.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">I **Value** morality because the resolution is centered on the evaluative term ‘moral obligation’ which calls into question what is moral. The concept of morality must come as an a priori to any moral obligation, because if something isn’t moral than it can’t be a moral obligation.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">To achieve morality, I will use the **Standard** of subjectivity. Prefer this standard for two reasons.</span>
# <span style="font-size: 10pt;">Morality is subjective. Morality is grounded in facts, and facts are just our interpretations of the ‘fact’. **Nietzsche 3[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn3|**[3]**]]** explains:</span>
<span style="font-size: 5pt;">Against positivism, which halts at phenomena -- "There are only facts" -- I would say: No, </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">facts are </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">precisely what there are not, only interpretations. W</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">e cannot establish any fact "in </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">itself" -- perhaps it is f</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">olly to want to do such a thing. In so far as the word </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">"knowledge" means anything, the world is kn</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">owable; but it is interpretable </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">otherwise, it has no meaning behind it, but countless meanings</span>__****<span style="font-size: 10pt;">. -- "Perspectivism."</span>**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Here, Nietzsche claims that there exists infinite interpretations, perspectives, and opinions of the truth and of morality. What is wrong and right varies from person to person, and thus morality itself is subjective. **Olson[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn4|**[4]**]]** furthers:</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">By</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">looking at one of Nietzsche’s specific postulations of perspectivism, we can get a better idea of precisely how this term applies to his philosophy and how it relates to the “truthfulness” of his other claims.</span>__** **__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">In</span>__****//__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Beyond Good and Evil</span>__//****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">, Nietzsche</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> begins with a chapter entitled “On the Prejudices of Philosophers.” Almost immediately he </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">begins to tear into the lack of integrity on the part of traditional philosophers who present their ideas as the product of pure reason. </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Nietzsche declaims, “they pose as having discovered and attained their real opinions through the self-evolution of a cold, pure, divinely unperturbed dialectic</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">: while what happens at bottom is that a </span>//<span style="font-size: 5pt;">prejudice</span>//<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, a notion, an ‘inspiration,’ generally a desire of the heart sifted and made abstract, is defended by them with reasons sought after the event” (//Beyond Good and Evil//, which will be referred to as </span>//<span style="font-size: 5pt;">BGE</span>//<span style="font-size: 5pt;">,I.5). </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Thus, philosophical insights are not the universal claims to truth that philosophers have presented them as and wished them to be. </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The philosophy of an individual is precisely that, not a product “of a cold, pure, divinely unperturbed dialectic.</span>__**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Nietzsche claims that because each individual has their own perspective of what is good and bad, than their outlook establishes their morals, not pure philosophical rhetoric by someone else’s perspective. These differences in morality alone prove the notion of perspectivism and for that reason morality is subjective. Thus to uphold morality, subjectivity must be used.</span>

2. Moral obligations are subjective. **Zimmerman[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn5|**[5]**]]** writes:

<span style="display: block; text-align: left;"><span style="display: block; text-align: left;"><span style="font-family: NewCenturySchlbk-Roman,serif; font-size: 5pt;">It is with overall moral obligation that the </span>//<span style="font-family: NewCenturySchlbk-Italic,serif; font-size: 5pt;">morally conscientious </span>//<span style="font-family: NewCenturySchlbk-Roman,serif; font-size: 5pt;">person is primarily concerned. </span>**__<span style="font-family: NewCenturySchlbk-Roman,serif; font-size: 10pt;">When one wonders what to do in a particular situation and asks, out of conscientiousness, ‘What ought I to do?’, the ‘ought’ expresses overall moral obligation. ‘Ought’ here is a contrary of ‘wrong’. Conscientiousness precludes deliberately doing what one believes to be overall morally wrong.</span>__**</span></span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Here Zimmerman notes that moral obligations are based on one’s belief of right and wrong. Because everyone believes their own set of right and wrong, and their own forms of morals, than everyone’s moral obligations of what they ought to do are based fundamentally on their subjective morals. This idea is furthered by **Ross[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn6|**[6]**]]**:</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">When people express different opinions about the rightness or wrongness of an act, the difference is</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">often </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">due to</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> the fact that one of them is thinking of objective and the other of </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">subjective rightness. The recognition of the difference</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">between the two </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">is therefore in itself important as tending to reconcile what might otherwise seem irreconcilable differences of opinion.</span>__**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Therefore, because people do have opposing opinions on what is right and wrong, there exists such subjective obligations, rather than purely objective ones. Therefore because there are both subjective morals and obligations, subjectivity not only upholds the value and resolution, but allows for competing interpretations of morality.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Thus the **Burden** for the affirmative will be to prove that some individuals establish their own moral obligations to assist others in need. Insofar as I prove a general amount of people will such obligations, I will win this round. The negative burden is to either prove that the Will to Power isn’t a moral obligation or that no individual has a moral obligation to assist people in need.</span>

**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Observation 1:</span>**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> As the affirmative, I only have to prove that such an obligation exists. Whether the obligation actually helps others, or other excessive burdens would be extra-topical. Insofar as any such obligation exists you must affirm.</span>

**Contention 1:** Exercising the Will to Power

# A. Self-reflective obligations
<span style="display: block; text-align: left;">
</span><span style="display: block; text-align: left;"><span style="display: block; font-size: 10pt; text-align: left;">The whole philosophy of Nietzsche and thus the subject moral obligation relies on the Will to Power. This concept of the Will to Power encourages people to only do what they themselves justify as moral. **Nietzsche 42** writes:</span></span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">One must subject oneself to one’s own test that one is destined for independence and command</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, and do so at the right time. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">One must not avoid one’s tests</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, although they constitute perhaps the most dangerous game one can play, </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">and are in the end tests made only before ourselves and before no other judge. Not to cleave to any person, be it even the dearest</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">– every person is a prison and also a recess. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Not to cleave to a fatherland, be it even the most suffering and necessitou</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">s</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> – it is even less difficult to detach one’s heart from a victorious fatherland. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Not to cleave to a sympathy, be it even for higher men</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, into whose peculiar torture and helplessness chance has given us an insight. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Not to cleave to a science</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, though it tempt one with the most valuable discoveries, apparently specially reserved for us. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Not to cleave to one’s own liberation</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, to the voluptuous distance and remoteness of the bird, which always flies further aloft in order always to see more under it – the danger of the flier. Not to cleave to our own virtues, nor become as a whole a victim to any of our specialties, to our “hospitality” for instance, which is the danger of dangers for highly developed and wealthy souls, who deal prodigally, almost indifferently with themselves, and push the virtues of liberality so far that it becomes a vice. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">One must know how to conserve oneself – the best test of independence.</span>__**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The means of implementing the Will to Power is for each individual to exercise it themselves and self-justify their morals and obligations based on their own independent rationale, without influence from others. Hence, each individual will have their own moral obligations.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Furthermore, allowing people to exercise their Will is not only acceptable under Nietzschean ethics, but rather necessitated. The subjective moral guideline that the Will to Power establishes will be ethical and affirm the resolution.</span>

# B. Willing to assist people in need
<span style="display: block; text-align: left;">
</span><span style="display: block; text-align: left;"><span style="display: block; font-size: 10pt; text-align: left;">People will inherently uphold this individual moral obligation to assist others in need. Many of the prominent affirmative authors have already exerted their Will to Power and solitarily justified their moral standards which resulted in helping others in need. Philosophers such as Singer and Korsgaard have self-justified their moral obligations. Even further many parents have justified their moral obligation to assist their children in need. The list of examples goes on and on, but the general principle is that through their own self-justification many people already do have the moral obligation to assist people in need, and thus you must affirm. Insofar as a general amount of individuals have such moral obligation you must affirm.</span></span>

# C. Infinite possibilities
<span style="display: block; text-align: left;">
</span><span style="display: block; text-align: left;"><span style="display: block; font-size: 10pt; text-align: left;">If you don’t believe the high possibility of a general amount of people willing a moral obligation to assist people in need, the fact that the universe is infinite in size makes it one hundred percent true. **Bostrom[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Affirmative/Aff%20-%20Nietzsche%20Will%20to%20Power.docx#_ftn7|**[7]**]]** writes:</span></span>
<span style="display: block; text-align: left;">
</span>
<span style="display: block; text-align: left;"><span style="display: block; text-align: left;">**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Recent </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">cosmological </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">evidence suggests that the world is</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">probably </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">infinite</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 5pt;">. </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Moreover</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 5pt;">,</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> [If] </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">the totality of physical existence </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">[it </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">is</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">]indeed </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">infinite</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, in the kind of way that modern cosmology suggests it is, then </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">it contains an infinite number of galaxies, stars, and planets. If there are an infinite number of planets then there is, with [a] probability [of] one, an infinite number of people. Infinitely many of these people</span>__**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **__are__** </span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">happy, infinitely many are [and] unhappy. Likewise for other local properties that are plausible </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">candidates for having value</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, pertaining to person</span><span style="font-family: 'Cambria Math',serif; font-size: 5pt;">‐</span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">states, [or] lives, or entire societies, ecosystems, or civilizations—there are infinitely many democratic states, and infinitely many that are ruled by despots, etc.</span></span></span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Insofar as there is a probability of one that there exists an infinite number of people, an infinite many of these people will exercise their Will to Power to establish their moral standards, moreover, an infinite number of those people will Will to assist others in need, and thusly an infinite amount of people will take it upon themselves to establish a moral obligation to assist a general quantity of people in need. Because of the infinite possibilities in the universe and the nature of the Will to Power in a Nietzschean paradigm, you must affirm.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Finally, if the debate comes to a wash, presume affirmative, because with the risk of offense of an infinite universe, the moral obligation will exist and thus affirm.</span>

**Overall:** <span style="font-size: 10pt;">Because morality is subjective, and Nietzschean ethics takes this into account, Nietzschean ethics will be the best philosophy to use in this round. Furthermore, the Will to Power establishes a subjective moral obligation, which directly coincides with the ethical framework. Finally, there exists a moral obligation to assist people in need under the Will to Power. Hence, I affirm.</span>

