**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Value: Morality</span>**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The resolution is centered on the evaluative term moral obligation, which necessitates morals.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">My **standard** for upholding morality is **deontology. Kant[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn1|**[1]**]]** writes:</span>

**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">Every rational being, exists as an end in himself </span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">and not merely as a means to be arbitrarily used by this or that will. </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">Beings whose existence depends not on our will but on nature have, nevertheless, if they are not rational beings, only a relative value as means and are therefore called things</span>__****__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">. On the other hand, rational beings are called</span>__****__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">persons</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;"> inasmuch as </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">their nature</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;"> already </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">marks them</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;"> out </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">as ends in themselves</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Therefore, in order for people – rational beings, to have any morality ascribed to them, we must seek to treat them as ends in themselves. Furthermore, the reason of giving them value is explained in the **Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn2|**[2]**]]**.</span>

<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 3pt;">The most influential position on these issues is found in the moral philosophy of Immanuel Kant (1785, 1788, 1797). Indeed, most contemporary discussions of respect for persons explicitly claim to rely on, develop, or challenge some aspect of Kant's ethics. </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">Central to Kant's ethical theory is the claim that all </span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 3pt;">persons are owed respect just because they are persons, that is, free rational beings. To be a person is to have a status and worth that is unlike that of any other </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">kinds of being</span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 3pt;"> it </span>**__<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 10pt;">is to be an end in itself with dignity. And the only response that is appropriate to such a being is respect. Respect (that is, moral recognition respect) is the acknowledgment in attitude and conduct of the dignity of persons as ends in themselves. </span>__**<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">Respect for such beings is not only appropriate but also morally and unconditionally required: the status and worth of person is such that they must always be respected. Because we are all too often inclined not to respect persons, not to value them as they ought to be valued, one formulation of the Categorical Imperative, which is the supreme principle of morality, commands that our actions express due respect for the worth of persons: “Act in such a way that you treat humanity, whether in your own person or the person of any other, never simply as a means but always at the same time as an end” (</span>//<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">Grundlegung zur Metaphysik der Sitten</span>//<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;"> (</span>//<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;">Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals)</span>//<span style="background-color: white; font-size: 5pt;"> (1785/1996, 4:429). Our fundamental moral obligation, then, is to respect beings; morally right actions are thus those that express respect for beings as ends in themselves, while morally wrong actions are those that express disrespect or contempt for beings by not valuing them as ends in themselves (Wood 1999). In addition to this general commandment, Kant argues that there are also more specific duties of respect for other persons and self-respect, to which we'll return. For now, we must address the question, What is it to be an end in itself and to possess dignity?</span>

**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The negative burden</span>**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> is to prove the resolution false. The traditional value/criterion model is only a means to this end, thus if the negative can prove this independently, it is sufficient for a negative ballot. Prefer this burden for two reasons:</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">1. As the true/false burden is a factual negation of the resolution, it stands prior to any other evaluation. In order to provide any other correct understanding of the resolution this problem must first be solved, and the burden is central to any educational value to be derived from this debate, as any other means would only be scraping the surface of the philosophical depth of the resolution. </span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">2. A true/false burden is the most predictable one to be posed as the resolution is the only resource either debater is provided with pre-round, and the understanding of the truth or falsity of a statement is the most intuitive understanding possible, as it requires no presuppositions other than what is provided by the most basic definition of the resolution.</span>

**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Observation 1: </span>**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">In order for a moral obligation to be so, it must be moral. Therefore if a moral obligation is immoral either through its means, its ends, or inherently, it cannot be a moral obligation and thus you must negate on face. Because moral obligations have to be moral, then moral obligations cannot be immoral. Proving moral obligations are immoral will be reason enough for voting negative.</span>

**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Observation 2: </span>**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">An axiom of deontology is that if an action is obligatory then it is possible. **Macnee[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn3|**[3]**]]** writes:</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Kant said that it was not our duty to do what is impossible for us to do. For Kant, the fact that we ought to do something means that it is logically possible to do –</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">‘ought’ implies ‘can’</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">. </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">Moral statements are prescriptive; they prescribe an action.</span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> If ‘ought’ implies ‘can’ then the statement, ‘I ought to do x’, implies that ‘I can do x’.</span>__**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">This is why we’d never say that a quadriplegic has a moral obligation to save a drowning person or that a person in Los Angeles has a moral obligation to stop a carjacking in New York. Systems of morality that obligate us to bring about something but don’t permit us to do so are nonsensical. It follows from the contrapositive of this axiom that if an action is not possible then it is not obligatory. It is my sole thesis that it is impossible to assist more than one person in need. </span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Therefore: **If the negative can prove that moral obligations to assist people in need are at some point impossible to fulfill, then you vote negative, as the affirmative would not be able to show that we had a moral obligation to perform that action.**</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Furthermore: If there is no affirmative offense at the end of the round you presume negative as the affirmative would have failed their converse burden to prove the resolution true. Further, if the negative can prove that assisting people in need is merely permissible, not obligatory, then you vote negative as we would not have the obligation to assist people in need. Insofar as any specific part of the case fulfills the burden of proving the resolution false then you vote negative. </span>

**Contention 1**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">: </span><span style="font-size: 11pt;">In an infinite universe, we cannot fulfill all obligations</span>

# <span style="font-size: 11pt;">a. Infinite Universe Paradigm</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The likelihood of an infinite universe implies that there are an infinite number of people in the universe that are in need. **Bostrom**</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn4|[4]]]</span><span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **1** writes:</span>

**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">“</span>****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Recent </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">cosmological </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">evidence suggests that the world is</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">probably </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">infinite</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 5pt;">. </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Moreover</span>__****__<span style="font-size: 5pt;">,</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> [If] </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">the totality of physical existence </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">[it </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">is] </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">indeed </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">infinite</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, in the kind of way that modern cosmology suggests it is, then </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">it contains an infinite number of galaxies, stars, and planets. If there are an infinite number of planets then there is, with [a] probability [of] one, an infinite number of people. Infinitely many of these people</span>__**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **__are__** </span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">happy, infinitely many are [and] unhappy. Likewise for other local properties that are plausible </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">candidates for having value</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, pertaining to person</span><span style="font-family: 'Cambria Math',serif; font-size: 5pt;">‐</span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">states, [or] lives, or entire societies, ecosystems, or civilizations—there are infinitely many democratic states, and infinitely many that are ruled by despots, etc.**”** </span>


**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Bostrom 2</span>**<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> furthers:</span>


**__<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">If there are an infinite number of planets then there will be—with probability one—an infinite number of people, since each planet has finite non-zero chance of giving rise to intelligent life.</span>__**<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 6pt;">In fact, in an infinite universe it seems that there will be an infinite number of people spontaneously materializing in gas clouds or from black hole radiation, since </span>**__<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">the probability of such occurrences, although extremely small, is nevertheless finitely greater than zero and would thus be expected to happen infinitely many times in a universe that contains an infinite number of [planets],</span>__**<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 6pt;">gas clouds and black holes. (See e.g. [4], p. 19; but also [5].) Of course, </span>**__<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">it is vastly more probable for intelligent creatures to evolve on a planet than to spontaneously materialize by random combination of elementary particles. Infinitely many of these people will be happy, infinitely many will be unhappy, and likewise for other such </span>__**<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 5pt;">local </span>**__<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">properties that pertain to person</span>__**<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 1pt;">-</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 5pt;">states, lives, or entire societies or civilizations</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 1pt;">—</span><span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 5pt;">there will be infinitely many democratic ones, infinitely many ruled by malevolent dictators, etc.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The affirmation ascribes moral obligations to each individual in need, and since the universe in infinite, there exist people in need who are physically unreachable from one another. This then follows that we would prescribe obligations to individuals that are impossible to fulfill. But no moral obligation is impossible to fulfill, and hence assisting people in need is not morally obligatory. </span>

# b. Finite Universe Paradigms

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Even if the universe is finite, we should not accept moral obligations that are conditional on the shape or size of the universe, **Bostrom 3** writes:</span>

**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">“</span>****__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Contemporary cosmology </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">is in considerable flux, so its conclusions </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">should be regarded as tentative. But it is </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">definitely </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">not reasonable, in light of the evidence we currently possess, to assume that we do not live in a[n]</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> canonically </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">infinite world. And that is sufficient for the predicament to arise. Any ethical theory that fails to cope with this</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">likely </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">empirical contingency must be rejected. We should not accept an ethical theory which [is], conditional on our current best scientific guesses about the size and nature of the cosmos</span>__**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">, </span><span style="font-size: 5pt;">implies that it is ethically indifferent whether we cause or prevent another holocaust.”</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Therefore even if the universe isn’t infinite, we cannot accept ethical theories based on finite guesses of the universes size that neglect the possibility of others. Hence, if you don’t accept sub-point a, then you must reject their ethical theory instead.</span>

**Contention 2:**<span style="font-size: 11pt;">Moral Obligations come into conflict</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Even if the universe is finite, it is impossible to fulfill our obligation to assist the other without sacrificing our obligation to the other others. **Derrida**<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 10pt;">[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn5|[5]]]</span> writes:</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">“As soon as I enter into a relation with the absolute other, my absolute singularity enters into relation with his on the level of obligation and duty. I am responsible to the other</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">as other, I answer to him and I answer for what I do before him. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">But</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">of course, </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">what binds me</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">thus in my singularity </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">to the absolute singularity of the other, immediately propels me into the space or risk of absolute sacrifice. There are also others, an infinite number of them,</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">the innumerable generality of others </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">to whom I should be bound by the same responsibility,</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> a general and universal responsibility (what Kierkegaard calls the ethical order). </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">I cannot respond to the call, the request, [or] the obligation</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, or even the love </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">of another without sacrificing</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">the other other, </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">the other others</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">. Every other (one) is every (bit) other [tout autre est tout autre], every one else is completely or wholly other. The simple concepts of alterity and of singularity constitute the concept of duty as much as that of responsibility. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">As a result, the concepts of responsibility, of decision, or of duty, are condemned a priori to paradox, scandal, and aporia. </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">Paradox, scandal, and aporia </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">[which] are themselves nothing other than sacrifice, the revelation of conceptual thinking at its limits,</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">at its death and finitude**__.__** </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">As soon as I enter into a relation with the </span>__****__<span style="font-size: 5pt;">other, </span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">with the gaze, look, request, love, command, or call of the </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">other, I know that I can respond only by sacrificing ethics, that is, by sacrificing whatever obliges me to also respond, in the same way, in the same instant, to all the others.”</span>__**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Hence we can never assist people since when I commit any attention to assisting one person I sacrifice my infinite obligation to assist others. But no moral obligation is impossible to fulfill, and hence assisting people in need is not morally obligatory.</span>

**Contention 3:** Moral obligations aren’t moral

3. a. <span style="font-size: 11pt;">Coercion of a moral obligation strips one’s liberty.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Universal moral obligations force individuals to do a certain actions. Professor Kluge argued against this by saying that ‘the person who acquires the obligation must be able to refuse it’ and that free will is always applicable. This ideology came under attack by Harry Lesser, who proved that there are some obligations in life that have no free will and are purely forced obligations. He provides a relatable example of such action. **Lesser[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn6|**[6]**]]** reads:</span>

<span style="font-size: 5pt;">“To this one could reply that, although the principle is not a logically necessary one it is nevertheless true, and the cases just mentioned are evidence of its truth. But there are counter-examples to this, of at least two sorts. </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">One is the obligation to members of one's family: one may choose one's spouse, and choose to have children, but one does not choose one's parents or siblings. Yet</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, although it is a matter of argument as to what one's obligations are, it is hard to deny that </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">one has some obligations, or that they are partly unilateral: one may have fewer obligations to a cruel and neglectful parent, but one still has some which are unavoidable.”</span>__**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">This nonconsentual moral obligation is taken one step further. **Nozick[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn7|**[7]**]]** writes:</span>

<span style="font-size: 5pt;">“The claim that the proponent of the ultraminimal state is inconsistent, we now can see, assumes that he is a “utilitarian of rights.” It assumes that his goal is, for example</span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">, to minimize the weighted amount of the violation of rights in the society</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, and </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">[claims] that he should pursue this goal even through means that themselves violate people’s rights. Instead, he may place the nonviolation of rights as a constraint upon action,</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> rather than (or in addition to_ </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">building it into the end state to be realized. The position held by this proponent of the ultraminimal state will be as consistent one if his conception of rights holds that your being //forced// to contribute to another’s welfare violates your rights</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;">, whereas someone else’s not providing you with things you need greatly, including things essential to the protection of your rights, does not itself violate your rights, even though it avoids making it more difficult for someone else to violate them. (That conception will be consistent provided it does not construe the monopoly element of the ultraminimal state as itself a violation of rights.) That it is a consistent position does not, of course, show that it is an acceptable one.”</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Therefore, the affirmative’s moral obligation strips individuals of their human right to liberty, an inviolable right, which is immoral to violate. Thus the moral obligations are being inherently immoral toward the enablers and actors of such obligations.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> 3. </span>b. Positive Duties treat the actors as means to an end.

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Welfarist positions such as this treat others as means to an end. **Korman[[file:///C:/Users/Andoni/Documents/DEBATE%202011/Nov-Dec/Negative/Neg%20-%20Test%20Infinity%20Bitch.docx#_ftn8|**[8]**]]** explains:</span>

**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">The real problem with the welfarist</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> model is revealed when confronted by a diverse society containing weakly protected minority groups. Because the </span>**__<span style="font-size: 10pt;">approach focuses on general economic welfare while deemphasizing the broader rights agenda, it necessarily ignores the upholding of certain rights standards in favor of greater economic or welfare development.</span>__**<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> While this focus poses less of a problem in relation to positive rights,</span>[[http://www.uclalawreview.org/wordpress/?p=1419#_ftn53|[52]]]<span style="font-size: 5pt;"> the welfarist agenda unques­tiona­bly conflicts with the promotion of negative, or more natural and fun­damental, rights.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">By having people assist others in need, the affirmative is inherently using these actors of the resolution as a means to achieve the ends of assisting the people. This clearly isn’t moral under deontological theory, and thus the moral obligations in the affirmative world is immoral. Because it is immoral, you must negate on face in order to treat beings as ends in themselves.</span>

