<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Hence, it is morally prohibited to use deadly force.</span>

**<span style="font-size: 10pt;">Underview:</span>**

<span style="font-size: 10pt;">If I say I am Andoni, it would be true, because I am saying it. But if I were to say I am Tommy, it wouldn’t be true. The objective statement that I am Tommy doesn’t align with the subjective view that Andoni is saying it, and thus the statement is false. Similarly, morals function like this. If you objectively say that suffering, pain, or violence is bad, yet you commit pain, suffering, or violence, then the ethic is not moral, and thus the action cannot be moral. Insofar as the affirmative is using deadly force, they are subjectively saying that violence is okay. Yet the end of the deadly force is to stop their suffering and their abuser’s violence. Thus the objective end is to stop suffering. By using suffering to stop suffering, you fall into this contradiction, which Nagel exploits and shows that the action is NEVER moral.</span>

